docs.abstract: President Trump traveled to the border and Vice President Mike Pence went to the Capitol to dig in on a border wall, shattering talk of a compromise.
docs.snippet: President Trump traveled to the border and Vice President Mike Pence went to the Capitol to dig in on a border wall, shattering talk of a compromise.
docs.lead_paragraph: McALLEN, Tex. — President Trump traveled to the border on Thursday to warn of crime and chaos on the frontier, as White House officials considered diverting emergency aid from storm- and fire-ravaged Puerto Rico, Florida, Texas and California to build a border barrier, perhaps under an emergency declaration.

headline.main: White House Considers Using Storm Aid Funds as a Way to Pay for the Border Wall
headline.print_headline: White House Sees Storm Aid as Way To Pay for Wall

byline.original: By Michael Tackett and Julie Hirschfeld Davis

docs.abstract: The president has tried to use fear as the prime motivator both with American allies and Democrats in Congress. It has not worked well for him.
docs.snippet: The president has tried to use fear as the prime motivator both with American allies and Democrats in Congress. It has not worked well for him.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Richard M. Nixon once said, “People react to fear, not love; they don’t teach that in Sunday school, but it’s true.”

headline.main: Trump Once Said Power Was About Instilling Fear. In That Case, He Should Be Worried.
headline.print_headline: ‘One Tool in His Toolbox’: Overreliance Blunts Trump’s Fear Tactics

byline.original: By Michael Tackett and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: The 41st president was known in caricature as someone who mangled syntax. But in his hundreds of letters, he expressed a quiet and often poignant eloquence.
docs.snippet: The 41st president was known in caricature as someone who mangled syntax. But in his hundreds of letters, he expressed a quiet and often poignant eloquence.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the cameras were rolling, President George Bush was fond of saying that he was not the emotional type. But with a pen in his hand, he expansively let out his heartfelt and innermost feelings.

headline.main: George Bush: A Life Through Letters
headline.print_headline: George Bush: A Life Story Shared in Longhand

docs.abstract: In his Palm Beach cocoon, President Trump is in his most comfortable mode, friends and allies say: playing the host in front of an adoring crowd.
docs.snippet: In his Palm Beach cocoon, President Trump is in his most comfortable mode, friends and allies say: playing the host in front of an adoring crowd.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After two months spent scorching the earth in Washington and complaining about being cooped up in the White House, President Trump is planning to return this weekend to the one place where he knows he will receive a hero’s welcome for his troubles: Mar-a-Lago, his gilded club by the sea in Palm Beach.

headline.main: Trump Returns This Weekend to Mar-a-Lago, His Gilded Comfort Zone
headline.print_headline: After Long Time Away, President Plans Return To Gilded Comfort Zone

byline.original: By Katie Rogers and Annie Karni

docs.abstract: The president’s tweets were the latest indication that he was digging in for a protracted partial government shutdown.
docs.snippet: The president’s tweets were the latest indication that he was digging in for a protracted partial government shutdown.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump dug in on his demand for border wall funding as the partial government shutdown approached its first full week on Friday, threatening again to close the southern border and cut off aid to Central America if Congress continued to deny his administration the money.

headline.main: Trump Threatens to Close Border if Congress Won’t Fund Wall
headline.print_headline: Trump Says He’ll Close the Border if a Wall Isn’t Funded

byline.original: By Annie Karni and Nicholas Fandos

docs.abstract: President Trump’s apparent indifference to the 800,000 federal workers who are not being paid represents a marked contrast from how his predecessors handled shutdowns.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s apparent indifference to the 800,000 federal workers who are not being paid represents a marked contrast from how his predecessors handled shutdowns.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — He has talked about the need for “protection” along the country’s southern border. He has said he is willing to keep the government shut down indefinitely to ensure the funding of the wall he says will provide that protection. And he has complained about spending the holidays alone in the White House, with no one around with whom he could negotiate.

headline.main: As Trump Holds Firm on Shutdown, He Never Mentions One Group: Federal Workers
headline.print_headline: 13 Days, 800,000 Unpaid Workers and One Tweet Aimed at ‘Democrats’

docs.abstract: The two meetings between White House officials and Democratic congressional staffers showed in ways big and small how the distance between the two sides remains a wide gulf.
docs.snippet: The two meetings between White House officials and Democratic congressional staffers showed in ways big and small how the distance between the two sides remains a wide gulf.
docs.lead_paragraph: Vice President Mike Pence insisted on beginning the first meeting with a prayer, so the chief of staff to the Senate majority leader, Mitch McConnell, asked God “to bring us together” when negotiators met Saturday in Mr. Pence’s ceremonial office in the Eisenhower Executive Office Building.

headline.main: A Wall and Two Prayers, but Little Progress at Weekend Meetings on the Shutdown
headline.print_headline: Dueling Prayers Yield Little Progress at Negotiations to End Shutdown

byline.original: By Maggie Haberman and Annie Karni

docs.abstract: Republicans may be struggling to sell their $1.5 trillion tax cut to voters, but the law has helped unleash tens of millions from donors who benefited handsomely from it.
docs.snippet: Republicans may be struggling to sell their $1.5 trillion tax cut to voters, but the law has helped unleash tens of millions from donors who benefited handsomely from it.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Republicans are struggling to make the $1.5 trillion Trump tax cuts a winning issue with voters in the midterm congressional elections, but the cuts are helping the party in another crucial way: unlocking tens of millions of dollars in campaign donations from the wealthy conservatives and corporate interests that benefited handsomely from it.

headline.main: Trump Tax Cut Unlocks Millions for a Republican Election Blitz
headline.print_headline: Trump Tax Cut Pays Dividends For the G.O.P.

byline.original: By Jim Tankersley and Michael Tackett

docs.abstract: Administration officials are expected to begin the interview process for the job, which has always gone to an American, on Tuesday.
docs.snippet: Administration officials are expected to begin the interview process for the job, which has always gone to an American, on Tuesday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Ivanka Trump, the president’s eldest daughter and senior adviser, will play a role in helping to select the next head of the World Bank, the White House said Monday.

headline.main: Ivanka Trump to Help Choose New World Bank President
headline.print_headline: Ivanka Trump To Help Choose Next President Of World Bank

docs.abstract: The extended timeline is the latest sign of how the president was surprised when his top candidate, Nick Ayers, would not agree to the terms of the job the president requested.
docs.snippet: The extended timeline is the latest sign of how the president was surprised when his top candidate, Nick Ayers, would not agree to the terms of the job the president requested.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump extended his timeline on Tuesday for choosing a new chief of staff to succeed John F. Kelly, telling reporters that he was in “no rush” and that the search process could drag on for weeks as the White House scrambles to find a suitable candidate to lead the West Wing at a pivotal moment.

headline.main: Trump in ‘No Rush’ to Fill Chief of Staff Job
headline.print_headline: Trump Says He’s in ‘No Rush’ to Find New Chief of Staff

byline.original: By Annie Karni and Maggie Haberman
